The paper proposes a new neurally-inspired model for visual event analysis and prediction, which involves learning contextual representations through both top-down and bottom-up processes. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the model uses predictive coding, which is a technique commonly used in neural networks and machine learning, suggesting that it could also belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper also discusses the model's ability to outperform state-of-the-art performances in estimation and prediction tasks, indicating that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves natural language processing techniques, such as encoding and decoding contextual information, suggesting that it could also belong to the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
